postcontent: It will chamber and fire .38 Special cartridges, as the .357 Magnum was developed from the .38 Special. The magnum case is slightly longer (0.1 in) to prevent magnum rounds from being chambered and fired in handguns chambered for the .38 Special. The 586 has been available with 2½ in, 3 in, 4 in, 6 in, and 8⅜" in (64, 76, 102, 153, and 214 mm) barrel lengths as standard models and other barrel lengths either by special order from S & W's Performance Center custom shop, or acquired from or built by after-market gunsmiths. The Model 586 uses S & W's L (medium) revolver frame, with a K-Frame sized grip mated to a larger diameter cylinder. During the 1980s, Smith & Wesson developed its L-Frame line of .357 Magnums: the Model 581, Model 586, Model 681 and Model 686. The Model 581 had a fixed notch type rear sight, whereas the 586 used a target style adjustable rear sight. These handguns had a major effect on both law enforcement and sporting markets. title: For Sale:  USMC Rock Island M1903
postcontent: Excellant example of an early WWII US Marine Corps rebuilt M1903 service issue rifle. During WWII the R.F. Sedgley Company accepted and completed a contract to manufacture M1903 barrels for the U.S. Marine Corps. These were stamped behind the front sight with USMC over a date and an encircled "S" (the SedgleyMark). This barrel is dated 9-42 with front sight cover. The rifle was originally a late WWI Rock Island Arsenal M1903 service rifle in the Marine Corps hands. The WWII rebuild was most likely completed at a Marine Corps Ordance Facility between late 1942 and mid 1943. The Marine Corps rebuilt rifles do not have stock cartouches. The scant stock appears near new and is straight grained American black walnut marked with a small "c" in the cut off recess. It has a nickel steel receiver and double heat treated straight bolt. Rear sight leafs are polished bright. Trigger is early WWI "Krag" type. Butt plate is the smothed milled type. Black parkerized finish. Marine Corps care and field maintenance of rifles is exceptional and it shows in this piece. The bore is bright with sharp lands and grooves. Rifle shows only moderate service wear and is at least NRA Very Good. Head space is correct. Appearance and function is exceptional with exceptionaly smooth action. Metal and wood on this rifle is about 95% and the overall condition is outstanding!
